“Do you love yourself?”- the question I try to ask myself everyday. I’ll be honest…some times I do and some times I don’t. The days I don’t love myself the intrusive thoughts that begin with “what if” start to overwhelm my mind. But then I think, that’s exactly what they are, intrusive thoughts. They are meant to cause disruption and annoyance. The older I got I realized it’s not about if those thoughts come in or not (because they’re always going to be there) it’s about how I react to them. So on those bad days I show myself love. I rest, I surf, I cook, I read, I fish or take a walk outside. I learn to love myself again because how can I show love to the world if I can’t show it to myself?  Today, I can say I love myself. 🤎
.
So, do you love yourself? 
.

Are you interested in taking your longboard surfing to the next level? The application for our Moore Aloha Longboard Fall Mentorship Program with @aunty_megzzz is now open!! 

This mentorship program is open to girls ages 10-16, based in Oahu, Hawaii, with an intermediate surfing ability. This is a six-week commitment from August 26th through October 7th, meeting once every weekend (location will vary depending on condition and swell). We will be accepting 5 girls. 

🌺WHO IS OUR FEARLESS LEADER🌺

Megan Godinez, better known as Aunty Megz, is a professional longboarder from Waikiki, Oahu. She is a bright light and inspiration to our next generation of girls. The program is centered on sharing Aunty Megz’s guidance and perspective for respecting our ocean, learning the lineups, etiquette, surf technique, ocean awareness, women’s surf history, and becoming an ambassador of Aloha not only in the break but in our everyday life.

“Surfing has taught me a lot in life, especially patience. Surfing is a re-active sport not a pro-active sport. All we do is react to what the wave is allowing us to do. The second you try to force a maneuver that the wave is not allowing, the ocean will kick you off real quick. I want to share with the next generation to be able to understand that concept and carry it throughout their daily lives. These are things I didn't learn on my own. It was my constant hunger for listening and learning from the people who came before me.” - @aunty_megzzz 

Submit your application by August 13! Can’t wait to see some of you in the Fall!

I’m not sure if there’s anything that tests your patience like fishing…we fish one spot, nothing…fish another spot, little bites but still nothing…we kept moving up and down the beach. As we were fishing I then realized “fishing” is so much like life. When we don’t catch a fish it’s the universe saying “no”. We go through life trying new things, going through different avenues, switching fishing spots and sometimes it’s not the right time nor right place. But sometimes, sometimes with perseverance, resilience and patience you hit the honey hole! So remember when one “fishing spot” doesn’t work, reset your spirit, move to another spot and be patient. The right fish will bite at the right time.  Thanks for coming to my #MEGZtalk #comeauntyshowyou🩵🙏

Week 2👇🏾 for the @moorealoha longboard mentorship program. Our topic for the day was….dun dun dunnnn…NOSERIDING. I told them I would rather you commit, walk to the nose and fall then not try at all. I’ve been trying to relate every message in this program to everyday life. Today’s lesson was “when you fall from trying something new, know that it’s not a form of being unsuccessful, it’s a form of resilience and strength as long as you keep trying and constantly learning.” I’ve been surfing for 25+ years and I’m still learning and never want to stop learning! I used to love reading books. Going in and out of fantasies of what’s on paper to what’s in the real world. The true escape of reality yet opening your eyes to what could be. The metaphors, the similes, the analogies. Comparisons. Relativity. Seeing my “screen time” go down in the last month feels so rewarding, knowing I’m getting lost on a piece of paper rather than a “screen”. It’s refreshing; Rebuilding my creativity to envision what a certain character looks like rather than seeing a photo all too photoshopped or all too planned. 
.
It seems hypocritical to write this on a screen and not on paper.
.
But my love for books has now regrown. In a time where a lot things are surfaced and more of a transaction than a connection, pick up a book. Connect with a book. Let yourself envision a story the way you want to see it and connect back to your creativity of fantasies that have a beginning, middle, and an end….but never forget to look up and smell the roses right in front of you. 
.
Anywayyyysss Thanks for coming to my #MEGZtalk and who wants to start a book club?!? lol 😝 #books

I didn’t come from a big family of surfing. BUT we were/are water people. Fisher people, swimmers, divers, bodysurfing etc. Surfing somehow came natural to me. 
.
Sitting here reflecting back to when my surfing career was at its peak. I was only 14 YEARS OLD freshly out of middle school. Back then there wasn’t social media platforms to showcase our talent, to post a cool/ funny video or to post a 10 second clip of a banger move. I wrote. I wrote to every single surf company I could think of. Telling them who I was, my background, my budgets, my accolades, my goals. I remember getting some letters back saying “no”. Being rejected at that age was rough. I remember crying some times being bummed that no one wanted to sponsor me. But I never gave up. I never stopped writing. I kept surfing, and surfing for the love of it, not for a sticker on my board.
